{
  "texts": [
    "This, coupled with the fact that the tails of asset returns are not well modeled by a Gaussian distribution [Fam65], suggests that portfolio construction should consider higher moments than the first and second.",
    "While it is possible to construct small academic examples where mean-variance optimization does poorly due to its neglect of higher moments, simple mean-variance optimization does very well on practical problems.",
    "In [LB23] the authors extend Markowitz by maximizing exponential utility, but with a more complex Gaussian mixture model of asset returns.",
    "Such a distribution is general, in that it can approximate any distribution.",
    "Their method evidently handles higher moments, but empirically gives no boost in performance on practical problems."
  ]
}